{"/service/ndnp/cohi/batch_cohi_gothic_ver01/data/sn86066890/00513680697/1907122701/0426.xml":{"full_text":"GUNNISON NEWS-CHAMPION\nP et i B\nby\nGessiacs Iritane Getahiished ons.\nPROGRESS OF COUNTY, MINING,\nSTOCK AND VARIED INDUSTRIES\nInvestment with u-elhw of Accemphsh\nment m 1907\nFor ity awo issues of 1907 News\nChampion has spread abroad the\ncontinued story of Guunison county\u2019s\nprogress and magnilicent resources\nand opportanities for investment.\nA few words about the leading in\ndustries will, however, not be ariss\naud the ilustratioms anuexed give a\npictorial review of them\nThe prosperous condition of owr\nmining industry has revived talk of\nSome Good Lumber in Ber Canea.\nThe lumbering industry, while not extensive in our part of the\nwountaing, yet gives eiaployment to probably 150 laborers. The mills at\nKebler pass, Brush creck on Blue Mesa, at Ohio City, etc. have all cut\nlarge quantities of native lumber and much of this has been shipped to\nsupply ontside demand, a probable total of five million feet. Our native\nlumber is mainly valuable for Lome building and forest reserve laws\nshould be 8o changed as to prevent the indiscriminate slaughter of forests\nfor the benefit of distant communities.\nA String of Rainbow Trout\nGunnison and its incomparable\ntrout stream is rapidly becoming a\nSwitzerland of America A dozeu\nsummer resorts with excellent\naccommodations line the banks of\nthe stream and hundreds of delight\nful camping spots are i use from\nJune to September. Come out and\nenjoy the seasou in 1908\nFrobough-Buckey Wedding\nLast Thursday morning at nine\no'clock ocearred the wedding of\nMiss May Buckey and Mr. Vern 1.\nFrobaugh. The wedding was at the\nhome of the bride\u2019s parents Mr. and\nMrs. John E. Backey, while Rev.\nFather Kipp wnited them in the\nholy bonds of matrimony. They\ntook the morning train for Crawford,\nColo., the groom\u2019s home\nThe bride is the oldest danghter\nof Mr.and Mrs. John k. Buckey and\nthe groom is the only sonof Mr. and\nMrs. T. H. Frobaugh. Friends and\nrelations wish them any congrat\nulations and a long and happy wed\nded life.\nDivorces were granted from the\ncounty court this week to Lucy\nWilliams from George Williams and\nto Ida M. Tucker from John S\nTuocker\nPitkin, nestling among the rich mineral veins of U\ng among th limineral veins of Upper Quartz creek, has passed a prosperous season\nand looks to the fatare with confidence. The wonderful mining revival on Ohio creel](. but l\"ol()\\r t{:eree miles dis\ntant, .lma helpe business. Bowerman, with the new mill of the Abe Lincoln, under construction, the great en\nterprxin\u00ab' nl; |le( vnp Bird mine, mill and power plant the Navajo tunnel and other smaller \ufb01mpevts has\nstimulated industry while closer 5 the fown has been systematic d\u00e9v 1 o\nv as p elopment of mines i\navgur a bright business outlook. N\ni In Taylor Park, now v\u2018-n:.\"\u2018\u00ab'h\u2018! will] Pitkin by telephone, the season\u2019s work from Tin Cup to the Enter\nprise. will be more particularly doseribad in an article from our special correspondence next week 3\na swelter at Guunison, aud indeed\nit s strange that men with capital\ndo aot reali.e s maguihicent advaut- i\nages along that ine. With abuad-\nance of wet aud dry ores. singularly\nfortunate as 10 water power, fuel,\niron and Lhime fluxes, etc. and all\nwith a down hill pall, there is no\nother such site in the west for I|\ngreat smelting industry 1t is sowe\nthing 10 boost for\n\u201cTWENTY YEARS AGO\u201d\nAnd u\u2018.'.'r\"?.mm:y\"\"\"\"\u201c\nS Go Gill and family returned\nfrom Salt Lake City where they had\nspent the autumn\nThere occurred the wedding of\nGeo. W. Summers and Miss Nellie\nBoardetic at the home of the bride\u2019s\nparents.\nGunnison Lodge No. 39, 1. O O,\nI, elected L. N. Fountaine, N. G\nM G, Levi, V.G HM. Hu@, sec\nretary; S, G Gill, treasurer.\nA government timber agent nam\ned Travis accused a dozen or more\nol onr repatable citizens of all sorts\nof Jand frand and then got out of\ntown as fast as he counld.\nThe famous prize fight between\nJake Kilrain, champion of America,\nand Smith, champion of England,\ntook place in France and resuited\nafter 104 rounds in Kilrain's getting\nthe better of it, although the fight\nwas declared a draw\nThe Lecture Last Night.\nThe lecture on Wonders of Mod\nern Science, last night was a very\nfine entertainment. Prof. Clarke is\na magician with electricity and after\nwitnessing the marvels he exhibited\nit was not hgrd to imagine his\nprophesies of the future as coming\ntrae. The next number of the lec\nture course will be given by Prof.\nMavnard Lee Daggy on \u201cAnglo-\nSaxon Grit,\u201d the 30th of January.\nThe Pretty Town of Pitkia\nGUNNISON, COLORADD, FRIDAY, DECENMBER 27, 1997,\nThe hay erop of Guni--m will this yoor reach 704NN 100 s\nLvery year more land is boing By the 330 ranchmen of the district,\nand improved wethods incosase the tmnage. This is the finest native\nhav in the world and worth $lO a sa@. Of shis product 20,0000 tons or\nE2OO, (00 worth is surples hay for sals. Several bundred acres of alfalfa\nhave been seeded in lte years and this is proving splendid crop\nTwenty-five per cent move grain was seised this veor than last or o total\nof 25,000 hushels threshed, three fousds of which weas cate Gunuison\ncounty holde the record for Colorado am cats and barley Every vear will\nwee Increasing acreage planted.\nGUNNISON STOCK GROWERS\nPLAN BIG DELEGATION\n'Will go to Denver in Fasce to Help Settle Public Land\nSucsion. Ages e il Fo Lih of P\nThe mid-winter meeting of the\n|Gununison County Stock Growers'\nAssociation held at the court house\nSaturday afternoon was well at\n[tended and some interesting ques\ntionw were talked over. The mem\n{bers do not agree upon the forest\nreserve question or the leasing\nquestion or a number of other prop\nositions, but the debates were com\nducted in a fair apirit and the dele\n|gution_chosen t 0 attend the elete\n}-oaendiu meeting in Doaver Jou\nwary 20 is composed of earnest men,\n(who will endeavor to wolve the\nproblems for the good of all con\ncerned.\nThe meeting was called to order\nby president R. 11 Andrews, aboat\ntwo o'clock, there having been some\nconfusion in regard to the hour. L\nH. Easterly, former secretary, read\nI the minutes of the annual meeting\n,last June and C. L. Stone then read\nthe call for the mid-winter meeting.\nThe matter of an estray day was\ndiscussed. T. Stevens thought it\n(should not be necessary for cap\ntams and their assistants to ride the\nranges, but they ought simply to\ngather the estrays from corrals and\nfields as they passed. This agreed\nwith President Andrews\u2019 idea. W\nA. Gillaspey said this was the origi-\nInal plan. K. Lightley brought\n{out the point that close riding on\nthe range for estray day made vou\nlan easy mark for ranchman who\nwere too lazy to bring in their own\nIstock. 1. W. Gray proposed that\nthe date be left to the president, as\nlit was too early to predict the\n|weather. I L. Dollard said he was\nElk Mouantain Pilot \u2014A Jocal mer-\nchant wishing to supply the Christ\nmas demand for chickens wired a\ncommission house, \u201cExpress us 150\nhens.\u201d Monday's train brought inl\n150 hams, so now it's ham nrl\nnothing for his customers.\nwilling 10 ride the range if nec\nostary, but different ends of lhe;\nnty have winter at different\ntimes. In Crested Butte they need\noa estray day in December, around\nCastleton in early January and on\nthe lower Gunnison and P'owder\nher perhaps not till Febraary first.\nA. E. Hyzer wentioned the h\ufb02l\n\u201c\u2018I m'lwy hold two es\ndays 10 asvange this mater,\nA were olready 'Tding estray\nstock they would like to get rid of\nwhile if the round wup was in late\nJanuary, those around Jola might be\nready 1o turn out for spring. It was\n\u2018decided to have the president of the\nassociation set the day and it seem\ned to be the general opinion that\neach range association should make\nits own round up and the estrays be\nbrought only from corrals and fields\nto Gumnison as the most convenient\nexchange point\nAs delegates to Denver the fol-\nlowing were chosen:\nR. H. Andrews, chairman; J. J.\nCarpenter, Ralph Allen, lee Leh-!\nman, Rouviere, Geo. Eastman,\nllugene McGregor, Henry (\u2018rooks.\nT. W. Gray, W. A Gillaspey, D T\nSapp, W. L. Bennett A I Hyzer,\nOus Moore, 1.1 Easterly, George\nAnderson, B. 1. Dillard, Albert\nHildebrand, J. R Fsies, W T\nHartman, Henry Rausis, 11 F Lake\nJr. R. M. Cooper, Mergel-\nman, Herman Filebrecht and \\a.\u00bb\\\u00bb-!\nDoering.\nA motion was passed that the\nmembers present be empovered 1\nComtinued on Third Page\nThe season has been one of vnexampled prosperity in the Crystal river district of Guunison county. Be\nsides the quartz liining operations on Gaiena and Treasury mountains and at Crystal and Marble, the develop\nment of Gunuison's magnificent white marble deposit on Yule creek has begun in earnest Nearly a million\ndollars has been spert by the Colorado-Yale and the Crystal River Marble companies Splendid roads have\nbeen built, the broad gage railroad has entered the conuty up to the town of Marble. This splendid mill,\nwhich has been in operation since August is polishing and sawing the blocks of \u201csolid whitene&s.\u201d and the\nfame of its beauty and wutility has gone abroad until even the city of Cleveland. in far off Ohio, has given orders\nfor half a million in marble trimmings for its pablic buildings. Marble City promwises within a vear to rival\nGunnison as the metropolis of our county\nHarry Noel is visiting his mother.\n\u2019He is employed in New Mexico\nClistmes Pogren &2 A Qhdd\nOpening song by the S ool doy 1o the\nWorkd.\nChristmas Groetiog Lewnd W ebiwer\nAnthem hoir\nPrayer. The Pastor\nBeetation and Suug M- Butes e\nA Grand Christmas Cantata e twe parte\nTue bachausted astl U harnctors. Santa\nCians. barles Dures Bob. Geoe bastman\nSam. Elmer Bates\nFairy Queen Suowiake. Miss Biliel Berry\nbl\nChorus of Faires Many bistie Garls 1 Wiote\nwith stars ovown and wend\nSiwbad the sailor Walter W obiber\nAladdin. Kay Vau Ahon\nDistribBtion of bricks comtaining troat Mise\nbastman Class\nistribution of Gifis, Miss Bates (s\nTalk by the Supscimten dent George Hothor\nb\nBouedwtion by the Pastor\nThe program was very nicely ren\ndeved. The honors must e divided\nbetween Nanta Claus and the cluld\nren, they all did w0 well Those who\ntrained the children deserve much\ncredit for their careful work\n\nwews-Champion Correspoadence.\nWednesday, Dec. 25\nThe following program wus ren\ndered at the Fairview School house,\nTuesday evening, the 24th. It was\na real old fashioned district school\nentertainment, and over a hundred\nof the people ou Ohio Creek and sur\nrounding communities were present:\nSelutation Altred Heos\u00abi\nRecitations Helon Gray, Miss Mabel Wallace\nMusical Seicction Florvuee Leliman\nTableaus Cocil Giay, Hazel Besse. Tillie Eile\nBrecht.\nRecitations Hanel Lehman, Smith Lehman\nJossie Jones Willis Gillaspey\nDislogwe, Myra Maithy, Edith Gray, Masel\nLebman, Ralph Lehman, Clavence Lobmun,\nRecitaitions. Hattie bollard, Claresce Gitlas\n\u00bboy.\nS LY T\nof the Bealls, Girle of\nRecitations, Edith Gray., Ralph Lebwan,\ndomes, Garner Dollard.\nVielin Selection and aceompaniment Alma\nEasterly, Myra Malthy\nRecitations, Helen Besse, Cocil Gray\nMusical Selection, Jessie Jones,\nRecitations, Lottie Jones, Myra Malthy, sara\nEasterly Tillie Kilebrocht.\nMusical Sclection, Edith Giray\nRecitations, Clarence Lehiman, Jossie Jones\nMusical Sclection. Emma Eilebrechit\nRecitations Hazel Desse, Miss hate Davis\nMusical Solection Myra Malthy\nRecitation nelen Besse\nalegue, Florem Lebman, Helon Besse:\nHelon Gray, Emma Lilebreeht, Jossie Jones\u2019\nAlfred Bessic, Charley Lichtley\nViolin Selection and accompanimont. Alma\nEasterly. Edith Giray\n.o\nAnnual Stockholders\u2019 Mecting\nNotice is hereby given that the\nwmnaal meeting ol the stockholders\nof the Gunnison Valley lee company\nfor the election of directors and the\ntransaction of such other business us\nmav come belore the meeting will be\nheld at Ihe oflice of the company at\nthe residence of D. V. Pennington\nin the town of Gunnison, Colorado,\non Tuesday, the 7th day of January,\nA D 1907, at b o'cock p.m\nD V. Pessizaros, Pres\nDated December 8, 1907\nHarry Endner is spending the\nweek with Ivnver friends\nHOLIDAY PROGRAMS\nOF VARIOUS SCHOOLS\nMose of the Christones Spinit as Exhibited in the Soags\nand Recitations of Yudetide Gathesings Here\nand These Theough the County\nNew Marble Ml ea Crystal River\nNUMBER &2\nIW Ceorreapsadenss.\nWeduesday, [Mvember 25\nSanta Clavs visited Mt Carbou\nschool Tuesday afverncon where there\nwas a tree loaded with all the good\n|things that make little ones feel\nlhamw. Mise Paulson, the teacher,\nbad the children prepared 1o enter\nihm Nanita\nSong by the sebool \u201cGrim Ol Wigier\nRecstation by theee little wnos Nins\nWk\nr Rectution by oo Zeiglor Decomber\nby Walter Speankie. Decembor\nI Song. by school Jingle Bolls\nBeettation by Ray LaPlant. What Sauts\nClaus Said\n\u201cong by Nettie Gorman Couotieg the days\nikl Nmas\nRecitation by dubin Kilban Nas Thongit\nDoty LaPlant. Rueeling Deer\nHattie Elsie. \u201cFi ther Nmas Fay\nwrite Child\nKecitation Lizae Leiligor Opiuion\nSong by the School. \u201cOld Santa laus\nKeetation. Nettie Gorman, \u201cWho Filled the\nStocking\nThe program ended with games,\n\u2018and the teacher and visitors wished\neach other a werry Xmas. Great\npraise is due /Miss Paulson, who\nspared neither time nor ::L-. 10\nmake the afternoon enjoy. for all.\nMrs. Dohlman is running the Ku\nbler boarding house.\nAl Brown got his thumb badly\ncrushed last Monday.\nMrs. Williams aud Kate have gone\nto Erie to remain some time.\nJos. Hyland and Mart Gorman\nwere in Gunnison last week.\nSeveral Mt. Carbon folks left\n\u2019de-y to spend the holidays with\nrelatives.\nTheturk\u00a5-homhodn good at\ntendance. The winuers were Hob\nBillngn, Joe Bave Lal'loste\nTliucn Nan Kasper Pressler,\nJoe Starovitch and other.\nil\nGrammar Scheel\nThe following Christmas program\nwas rendered by the Atheneum Lit\nerary society of the Gunnison Gram\nmar school on the 20th,\nOpening song\nRoll eail Response questions.\nKecitation Eina Wright\nRecitation Irene Nugeider\nHistory of Christmas Viola henuison\nKeeitation Fern Friend\nLegend of Santa Claus Orion Woods\nRecitation Helon MeCormick\nSong School\nHistory of the Christmuas Tree Walter Webber\nRecitation Arloa Enduer\nOriginal Story Lorita Purrier\nMusic\nRecitaion Hazel Proflit\nChristmas Story Robert Barrett\nPaper Lo sprankle, Edwin Jones\nRecitation hate Daoyle\n\nThe Redmen and their guests\nWednesday night report a fine time,\nwith over .one hundred couples in\nattendance, who crowded Woodmen\nand Redmen halls B. B Lash\nbrook serverd an excellent supper.\nThe wnext big dance is Tuesday\nnight, New Year's eve, when the\nWomen of Wooderatt will hold a\nLall at Woodman hall\nC. 1. Bennett, of Bowerman, vis\nited our burg Sunday.","height":"20992","width":"15268"}}
